Reasoning: The paper deals with fixed point combinators and their beta-inconvertibility, which are concepts related to lambda calculus and logic. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science). The paper also discusses the infinitary lambda calculus and the construction of new fixed point combinators using modular building blocks, which are topics related to programming languages and compilers. Hence, cs.PL (Programming Languages) is another likely sub-category. The paper also introduces the concept of clocked Boehm Trees, which are used to refine the discrimination method for lambda-terms. This is a topic related to information theory and signal processing, which falls under cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also mentions Levy-Longo Berarducci trees, which are related to data structures and algorithms, falling under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Finally, the paper discusses the precision of the clock notion, which is a topic related to formal languages and automata theory, falling under cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory).
